      <hedline>
        <hl1>Lessons From Vietnam</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Peter Ham letter on Apr 28 article holds values and principles United States fought unsuccessfully for in Vietnam are beginning to flourish there, spurred by economic ties</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Case Study in Disaster for Tomorrow's Generals'' (front page, April 28):</p>
        <p>Maj. David M. Toczek should punctuate his West Point course on the Vietnam War with a class trip to that country. His students would learn firsthand that the economic sword is sometimes mightier than the military sword.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Case Study in Disaster for Tomorrow's Generals'' (front page, April 28):</p>
        <p>Maj. David M. Toczek should punctuate his West Point course on the Vietnam War with a class trip to that country. His students would learn firsthand that the economic sword is sometimes mightier than the military sword.</p>
        <p>The values and principles we fought unsuccessfully for in Vietnam are now beginning to flourish since the economic embargo was lifted in 1994 -- at a cost that does not include human life, national debt and political humiliation.</p>
        <p>PETER  HAM  Princeton, N.J., April 28, 2000</p>
      </block>
